Ok so please excuse me as I go off on an anime rant. For all of my friends who enjoy anime<CM> and more specifically shoujo drama romances (oh yeah we gettin' real specific like up in here)<CM> if you haven't seen White Album 2<CM> just go watch it. Don't question it<CM> just watch it. Then come back<CM> and we can have a nice little discussion about...<NL>SPOILERS AHEAD<NL><NL>This show! This freaking show has caused me no less then 10 heartaches. 10 I tell you! This might be one of the most well written love triangles I have ever seen<CM> and the beauty of that writing has made it an uber-successful VN in Japan. HOWEVER! The anime with its 13 bite sized episodes leaves you right smack dab in the middle of the story. No proper ending<CM> no closure<CM> no nothing. Just an extreme case of blue balls<CM> a desire to magically raise 2 million dollars for another season<CM> and one of the most sad endings I have ever seen. It's not sad because it's disappointing<CM> it's sad because of how realistic and true it is to the story and characters and that almost pisses me off more then lazy writing. Everything about this show<CM> from the writing to the animation to the voice acting to the brilliant use of coloring and imagery<CM> is a masterpiece<CM> and that's why I feel like it is a shame that there won't be more of it. <NL><NL>Overall though<CM> this show really did the romance genre proud. It handled each of the characters with care and respect<CM> and even the more minor characters were well developed and their action never seemed for the provoke plot progression. The art is absolutely stunning. The use of color and perspective really shines and you can tell the careful mix of storytelling and cinematography. This show does something very uncommon in that it actually handles sex and pda in a very respectful<CM> yet still sensual way<CM> it hits the middle ground very well and it is few and far between to show a well displayed sex scene that is both hot<CM> passionate<CM> and doesn't diminish the fact that it's two CHARACTERS having sex and not just total strangers. My only<CM> only complaint would be the ending<CM> that is not a stepping off point<CM> but merely a stair that must be climbed to get to the next part of the story<CM> which was continued in the VN. With the way they set up the anime<CM> they would have to do Haruka True ending<CM> which I am perfectly fine with<CM> even though I don't hate Setsuna. Honestly<CM> I'm not keeping my hopes up for a full second season<CM> but I do hope for some OVAs at least to work out the endings. Anyways just have to rave and rant<CM> if you're reading this then you must really care about my opinion<CM> thanks :)

Okay<CM> well<CM> what little hope I had for this movie is basically dead with this trailer. Visually? Stunning. Reminds me a lot of the anime<CM> with a few understandable creative liberties to make it look more real<CM> though nothing I mind. Aside from the puppetmaster inhabiting a clearly male body. That doesn't bother me too much<CM> given while the original puppetmaster did inhabit a female body<CM> the puppetmaster was genderless<CM> with a male voice. <NL><NL>What does bother me is that Motoko is being manipulated here. Yes<CM> in the original<CM> she was unhappy and stuck working for Section 9<CM> though that was because she was questioning her humanity<CM> and aside from her friends in Section 9<CM> she didn't really feel treated like a human<CM> just a machine. <NL>Having her actually being manipulated<CM> kind of destroys the plot<CM> given the puppetmaster is supposed to be created by section 6<CM> who is actually pulling its' strings until it gains sentience and betrays them<CM> then desperately trying to get it back. The only way I could see this plot working if both sides are corrupt<CM> which would really just seem like a lazy way of pulling the message of corrupt government<CM> when the original had such a strong and well written message about Motoko discovering her humanity and becoming a stronger person after merging with the puppetmaster<CM> trying to get the viewer to question just what it meant to be human<CM> which was a great and interesting philosophy. Whether or not you agree with those who read into some of the subtext as feminist (I've already spoiled so much of the movie that I won't go into it)<CM> the message about humanity is well defined<CM> and doesn't feel pretentious<CM> as it stands well through the film's storytelling<CM> as slow paced and somewhat cryptic<CM> for lack of a better word. <NL><NL>Just her being manipulated by Section 9 destroys the movie as an adaptation.
